          "id": 147524,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Sodium and Calcium</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 147525,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Potassium and Magnesium</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 147526,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Potassium and Calcium</span></span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">A medical student is preparing for her physiology exam, focusing on electrolyte distribution in the body. She is studying the most abundant intracellular cation and the most abundant intracellular divalent cation. Which of the following options correctly identifies these ions?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3623722",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33616,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. C) Potassium and Magnesium</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option C:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Correct. <strong>Potassium</strong> is the most abundant <strong>intracellular cation</strong>, and <strong>magnesium</strong> is the most abundant <strong>intracellular divalent cation</strong>, playing key roles in <strong>numerous cellular processes</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Option A:</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. Potassium is the most abundant intracellular cation, but phosphate is not a cation; it&#39;s an anion.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Option B:</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. <strong>Sodium</strong> is not the most abundant intracellular cation; it is more <strong>prevalent extracellularly.</strong> Calcium is not the most abundant intracellular divalent cation.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Option D:</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. Although <strong>potassium</strong> is the <strong>most abundant</strong> intracellular cation, calcium is not the most abundant intracellular divalent cation; magnesium holds this distinction.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">The objective is to identify the <strong>most abundant intracellular cation</strong> and <strong>divalent cation</strong>, which are crucial for <strong>understanding cellular functions</strong> and <strong>electrolyte balance</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Refer: Ganong&#39;s Review of Medical physiology 26<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 4, 5</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
