          "id": 31684,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Macroglial cells form the blood-brain barrier and are predominantly responsible for fibrosis in the central nervous system.</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31685,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Macroglial cells, while integral to the blood-brain barrier formation, do not play a predominant role in CNS fibrosis unless they become reactive, which is primarily mediated </span><span style=\"font-size:11.0pt;\">by other cell types.</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31686,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The blood-brain barrier is formed by endothelial cells, not macroglia, but macroglial cells are predominantly responsible for CNS fibrosis.</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31687,
          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Neither the formation of the blood-brain barrier nor the mediation of CNS fibrosis involves macroglial cells, as these functions are carried out by different cell types in the CNS.</span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 50-year-old woman with a history of multiple sclerosis presents with new-onset neurological symptoms. Her MRI shows areas of demyelination and gliosis. Considering the physiological and pathological roles of macroglial cells, which of the following is correct?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1779462",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33617,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. B) Macroglial cells, while integral to the blood-brain barrier formation, do not play a predominant role in CNS fibrosis unless they become reactive, which is primarily mediated by other cell types.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B:&nbsp;</strong>is correct. <strong>Macroglial cells,</strong> including astrocytes and oligodendrocytes, are involved in the formation and maintenance of the <strong>blood-brain barrier. However, CNS fibrosis, particularly in the context of diseases like multiple sclerosis, i</strong>s more complex and not predominantly mediated by myofibroblasts and when astrocytes become reactive.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A:&nbsp;</strong>is incorrect because while <strong>macroglial cells</strong> are involved in the formation of the <strong>blood-brain barrier</strong>, they are not predominantly responsible for fibrosis in the CNS. Fibrosis in the CNS is usually <strong>mediated</strong> by other cell types, such as <strong>myofibroblasts.</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C:&nbsp;</strong>is incorrect. The blood-brain barrier is indeed formed by a <strong>combination</strong> of <strong>endothelial cells, astrocytes</strong> (a type of <strong>macroglia</strong>), and <strong>pericytes</strong>, but macroglial cells are not the main mediators of CNS fibrosis.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D:&nbsp;</strong>is incorrect as it denies the role of macroglial cells in the blood-brain barrier formation. <strong>Macroglial cells</strong>, particularly <strong>astrocytes</strong>, play a <strong>crucial role</strong> in this aspect.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">This question assesses the understanding of the roles of <strong>different glial cells</strong> in the <strong>central nervous system</strong>, focusing on the <strong>physiological role</strong> of <strong>macroglial cells</strong> in the <strong>blood-brain barrier</strong> and their involvement in pathological processes such as <strong>CNS fibrosis</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"color:black;font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ref: Ganong's Review of Medical physiology 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 85</strong></span></p>",
