    {
      "id": 7935,
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 31708,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Oligodendrocytes &ndash; formation of the blood-brain barrier</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31709,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Schwann cells &ndash; support neuronal function in the central nervous system</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31710,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Astrocytes &ndash; form myelin sheath in the peripheral nervous system</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 31711,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Microglia &ndash; act as immune defense cells in the CNS</span></span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">A neurologist is explaining the roles of different glial cells in the central and peripheral nervous systems during a seminar.&nbsp;</span></span><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Which of the following pairs correctly matches the cell type with its primary function?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q9005231",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33618,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. D) Microglia &ndash; act as Immune Defense Cells in the CNS</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option D:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Correct. Microglia act as <strong>scavenger cells</strong> in the <strong>CNS</strong>, playing a role similar to <strong>macrophages</strong> in the <strong>immune system</strong>, cleaning up <strong>debris</strong> and <strong>dead cells</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">This image shows the <strong>four different types</strong> of <strong>glial cells</strong> found in the <strong>central nervous system</strong>: </span></span><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ependymal cells</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> (light pink), <strong>Astrocytes</strong> (green), <strong>Microglial cells</strong> (red), and <strong>Oligodendrocytes</strong> (functionally similar to Schwann cells in the PNS) (light blue).</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/28/6.jpg\" style=\"height:244px; width:300px\" /></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option A:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Incorrect. Oligodendrocytes are responsible for <strong>myelinating neurons</strong> in the <strong>CNS</strong>, not forming the blood-brain barrier.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option B:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Incorrect. <strong>Schwann cells</strong> myelinate peripheral nerves, not central nerves.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option C:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Incorrect. <strong>Astrocytes</strong> have many functions, including <strong>supporting blood-brain barrier</strong> <strong>maintenance</strong> and <strong>neuronal support</strong>, but they do not myelinate in the PNS.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">The objective is to <strong>recognize</strong> the <strong>distinct functions</strong> of various types of <strong>glial cells</strong> within the <strong>nervous system</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref: Ganong&#39;s Review of Medical physiology 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 85.</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
