          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Schwann cells and Ependymal cells</span></span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">A patient with a chronic neuroinflammatory condition presents with neurological symptoms that suggest both myelin damage and a robust immune response within the central nervous system (CNS). MRI findings are indicative of demyelinating plaques, and CSF analysis demonstrates the presence of cells involved in active phagocytosis. Which combination of glial cells is most likely associated with myelination and participation in the monocyte-macrophage system in this patient&#39;s condition?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8133650",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33614,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. A) Oligodendrocytes and Microglia</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option A:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Correct. <strong>Oligodendrocytes</strong> are responsible for <strong>myelinating neurons</strong> in the <strong>CNS</strong> and are implicated in the <strong>pathology</strong> of many <strong>demyelinating diseases</strong>. <strong>Microglia</strong> are the <strong>resident immune cells</strong> of the <strong>CNS</strong> and part of the <strong>monocyte-macrophage system</strong>, which become <strong>activated</strong> in response to <strong>disease</strong> or <strong>injury</strong> and can <strong>phagocytose debris</strong>, such as <strong>damaged myelin</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanations:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Option B:</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. <strong>Microglia</strong> and <strong>Astrocytes</strong> are <strong>both types</strong> of <strong>glial cells</strong> within the <strong>CNS</strong>; however, <strong>astrocytes</strong>, despite their <strong>supportive roles</strong> and reactive changes in the <strong>setting</strong> of <strong>CNS injury</strong>, are not primarily involved in myelination.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Option C:</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. Astrocytes provide structural support in the CNS, and Schwann cells are involved in <strong>myelination</strong> within the <strong>peripheral nervous system (</strong>PNS), not the CNS, and neither are part of the monocyte-macrophage system.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Option D:</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Incorrect.</strong> Schwann cells myelinate peripheral nerves, and ependymal cells line the <strong>ventricles</strong> of the <strong>brain</strong> and the <strong>central canal</strong> of the <strong>spinal cord</strong>. Neither are involved in the CNS&#39;s monocyte-macrophage system.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">To distinguish between the <strong>roles</strong> of <strong>CNS glial cells</strong>, particularly <strong>oligodendrocytes </strong>in <strong>myelination</strong> and <strong>microglia</strong> as part of the <strong>CNS immune response</strong> within the <strong>monocyte-macrophage system</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref: Ganong&#39;s Review of Medical physiology 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 85</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
